transcription.text:
Speaker 1: Thanks for calling Viagra. Clint speaking. How can I help you?

Speaker 2: Yeah, Clint. I have gotten charges on my credit card that are recurring and I don't want those to be.

Speaker 1: Okay. Let's pull up your account.

Speaker 2: Okay.

Speaker 1: Here's your name, Jim.

Speaker 2: That's it.

Speaker 1: Alrighty, Jim. I do have you pulled up here as one of our V.A.P.s.

Speaker 2: What's going on with your Viagra, Jim?

Speaker 1: I don't know how it went from what I paid for the first prescription and then you sent me.

Speaker 2: I just got charged two hundred and some odd dollars for a shipment.

Speaker 1: Okay. So...

Speaker 2: You are...

Speaker 1: So you're referring to the five dollar difference?

Speaker 2: I'm sorry, what?

Speaker 1: You're referring to the five dollar difference?

Speaker 2: No. I...

Speaker 1: Your first order was two hundred and eight dollars and ninety-five cents.

Speaker 2: Your last order was two thirteen ninety-five.

Speaker 1: That's a five dollar difference.

Speaker 2: I did not know it was recurring. So I didn't need or want...

Speaker 1: Let's talk about one thing first.

Speaker 2: Okay.

Speaker 1: So you're talking about the price.

Speaker 2: First, yeah, the price. I thought the original order was something under a hundred dollars.

Speaker 1: Not at all. Your first order was two hundred and eight dollars and ninety-five cents.

Speaker 2: And that order was placed on March twenty-third, 2005.

Speaker 1: Okay.

Speaker 2: And then you said you didn't know it was recurring.

Speaker 1: Well, it's not only, you know, it's up to you to set it up, you know,

Speaker 2: whether it's needed or you can choose when your orders do come out.

Speaker 1: Yeah.

Speaker 2: Well, at this end, you know, I haven't taken any initiative.

Speaker 1: The first, so I just got another supply of this stuff.

Speaker 2: I looked at my bank statement and I was surprised.

Speaker 1: Okay. So we'll stop it.

Speaker 2: It wasn't effective and I need to just terminate.

Speaker 1: Okay. Just terminate it.

Speaker 2: Anything else?

Speaker 1: Nope. That'll do.

Speaker 2: Okay. Have a nice day, sir.

Speaker 1: All right. Thank you.
